name: mockingbird
description: Distributed mocking service for fault simulations
description_good_justification:
Mockingbird is an open source distributed and programmable fault simulation mocking service.

It provides an extensible set of middleware layers that enable the simulation of variety of different service faults. The primary purpose of the framework is to allow consumers to test the way they handle services that exhibit uncertainty and instability.

Mockingbird is built so that it can be used as an NPM package. It can also be used as a stand-alone cli as well as part of a Serverless ecosystem by deploying it using serverless framework.

The current version supports adding new simulation layers. Future version will allow for extension of exhisting layers through extnesion of classes and interfaces.

vulnerability_report_process_justificati: https://github.com/cloud-custodian/cloud-custodian contains information on how to contact the security team
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: https://github.com/cloud-custodian/cloud-custodian readme has a security contact address for private reporting of security issues.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: we haven't had a security vulnerability reports per se, but we generally turn around any major bug issues within two weeks. security issues would be treated as high priority release breaking issues. we've had two contacts via our security contact address, both issues where actually questions, and were answered/resolved within 48 hrs.
build_justification:
Non-trivial build file in repository: <https://github.com/cloud-custodian/cloud-custodian/blob/master/Makefile>.

docker - Dockerfile
python - tox -e py37
build_common_tools_justification:
Non-trivial build file in repository: <https://github.com/cloud-custodian/cloud-custodian/blob/master/Makefile>.

for python tox, and docker
test_justification: 2500+ unit tests run per pull request
test_invocation_justification: we use the tox project for automating install and test execution. $ tox -e py37
test_most_justification: project has 90% code coverage, with all pull requests required to be within 10% of that.
test_policy_justification: pull requests are failed in ci unless they have adequate test coverage.
tests_are_added_justification: pull requests aren't merged unless ci status is passing which is also evidence of test coverage as coverage on changes is part of our ci process.
warnings_justification: we use flake8 for linting with python
warnings_fixed_justification: flake8 linting errors are considered failures in ci.
know_secure_design_justification: I'm unclear on how to document acceptably.
crypto_published_justification: project use of crypto is primarily through transport encryption (tis) and use of cloud crypto services (kms, keyvault, etc).
delivery_mitm_justification: https is used for all remote communication protocols per cloud provider sdks
static_analysis_justification:
we use 3 static analysis tools
 - flake8 (python) - https://github.com/PyCQA/flake8
 - bandit - https://github.com/PyCQA/bandit
 - semgrep with security-audit config  - semgrep.dev
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: both bandit and semgrep look for common issues wrt to vulnerabilities.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: static analysis is done on entire code tree per commit, and is part of ci validation for any changes/pull-requests
static_analysis_often_justification: static analysis is done per commit
dynamic_analysis_justification: all user inputs are processed with multiple layers of validation, a structural parser and jsonschema validation, however we do not formally fuzz those inputs. however the usage of a memory safe language seems to mitigate the majority of concerns addressed by such.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: there are sanity asserts per input processing
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: we have per pull request unit tests, as well as nightly functional tests automated.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
